Part I - (Prosper Loan Data Exploration)¶

by Ugwu Paulinus Uche¶

Introduction¶

This section is on the exploration of a financial data set that is related to loan, borrowers, lenders, interest rates, credit scores, etc, from Prosper Marketplace Inc, a San Francisco, California based company specialised in loans at low interest rates to the borrowers. Visualizations would be deployed to discover patterns, structures and underlying distributions of the financial data

# Splitting ListingCreationDate column into year,month,day,time

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Shape method shows that there are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in the features that affect the borrowers APR and the loan status

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • IncomeRange - The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  • DebToIncomeRatio - The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).
  • ProsperRating (Alpha) - The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • Listing category and the employment status of the borrower
  • Principal

In [33]:
# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = df_loan, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount','DebtToIncomeRatio'], 
                x_vars = ['Term','ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'EmploymentStatus'], height = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid);
plt.xticks(rotation=30);

<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>

Borrower APR didnt change in its median value, but the loan original amount showed a steady increase , but dropped generally across employment status

  • How does borrower APR and debt to income ratio affect loan status.
  • was the prosper rating efficient for the above findings?

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It was observed that completed loans are loans with low or high borrower APR (as there are much green clusters in these region) these features also have low debt to income ratio, showing that it is borrowers with low debt to income ratio that are more frequently granted loans. The prosper rating proved to be efficient as it affirmed this fact.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The Loan original amount is observed to reduce with reducing income range and goes a bit up for borrowers without employment or are self employed. This can be postulated to mean that self employed or borrowers without income are given considerable large amount of loans. This might be because of conceived investments and new business ventures.

While this might be true borrower APR is observed to be more for self employed and borrowers with no income and reduces as income range increases. This questions fairness, but on second thoughts, Lenders would see a lower level of risk when you have more stakes in property(assets) i.e collaterals.

Generally, a larger loan payment would hence mean lower interest rate from analysis.

Conclusions¶

  • Larger loan payment means lower interest rates.
  • Completed loans with respect to terms are loans with high or lower interest rates. This implies that the no employment category and borrowers with high income have more tendency to complete their loans.
  • Prosper rating was efficient in rating and hence trustworthy to be used as criteria for judging in rendering loan and predicting status/outcome
